If `kdamond_need_stop` is true, the loop breaks.
It jumps to `done:`.
It sets `call_controls_obsolete = true`.
Then it calls `kdamond_call(ctx, true)`.
This processes the pending `damon_call` request, cancels it (`cancel = true`), and calls `complete(&control->completion)`.
Then `damon_call` wakes up and sees `control->canceled = true`, so it returns `-ECANCELED`.
This is exactly the correct and safe behavior!

What if `damon_sysfs_turn_damon_on` leaks `repeat_call_control`?
Yes, `err = damon_call(ctx, repeat_call_control); return err;` where `err` was `0` before the call. It ignores the return value of `damon_call`.
If `damon_call` fails (e.g. returns `-ECANCELED`), the dynamically allocated `repeat_call_control` is not added to the list and thus `kdamond_call()` never frees it, causing a memory leak.
